  "slug": "blanquette-de-veau",
  "title": "Blanquette de veau",
  "subtitle": "Classic French white braise with cream and egg yolk sauce.",
  "excerpt": "Pork shoulder simmered gently in stock with aromatics, then finished in a velouté enriched with cream and egg yolk. The meat stays pale and the sauce coats a spoon. French bourgeois cooking at its most precise. Serves four.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Blanquette de veau. The dish is one of the grande cuisine classics documented in Auguste Escoffier's Le Guide Culinaire (1903, public domain) and in Prosper Montagné's Larousse Gastronomique (1938). Traditionally made with veal shoulder; pork shoulder is used here as a widely available substitute with comparable technique and texture.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Blanquette is a white braise. The meat is not browned; it is blanched in boiling water, rinsed, then simmered gently in stock. The pallor is deliberate. The final sauce, a velouté enriched with cream and egg yolk, should be ivory-white and smooth. Served with rice or new potatoes, it is one of the most satisfying dishes in the French repertoire.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The liaison of cream and egg yolk is added at the very end, off the heat. The pan must not return to a boil once the liaison is in. This is the point where the dish can fail; watch the temperature carefully.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
