      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Blanch and simmer the meat",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Put {{pork-shoulder}} of pork cubes in a large saucepan. Cover with cold water, bring to the boil, then drain and rinse the meat under cold water. Return to the pan with {{onion}} onion, {{carrot}} carrots, {{celery}} celery, {{garlic}} of whole garlic cloves, {{thyme}} of thyme, {{bay-leaves}} of bay leaves and {{stock-chicken}} of stock. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Bring to a gentle simmer; skim off any foam. Cook on low heat for 1 hour until the meat is tender.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cook the mushrooms and make the velouté",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Remove the meat and strain the cooking stock; discard the aromatics. Add {{mushrooms-button}} of mushrooms to the strained stock and simmer for 5 minutes; remove and set aside. Melt {{unsalted-butter}} of butter in a saucepan over medium heat. Add {{plain-flour}} of flour and cook, stirring, for 2 minutes. Gradually whisk in 600 ml of the cooking stock until smooth. Simmer for 10 minutes, whisking often, until thick enough to coat the back of a spoon.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the liaison and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Whisk {{double-cream}} of double cream with {{egg-yolks}} egg yolks and the juice of {{lemon}} lemon in a bowl. Remove the sauce from the heat. Slowly whisk the liaison into the hot sauce. Return the meat and mushrooms to the sauce. Season with {{white-pepper}} of white pepper and adjust salt. Reheat very gently, do not boil. Scatter with parsley if using.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Add the liaison off the heat, then reheat on the lowest possible setting without boiling. If it has scrambled, push through a fine sieve.",
              "cause": "Sauce was too hot when the egg and cream were added, or the pan returned to the boil.",
              "symptom": "Sauce scrambled or curdled after adding liaison"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Use only 600 ml of the cooking stock in the velouté. Simmer the sauce longer before adding the liaison.",
              "cause": "Not enough roux, or too much stock used.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Pork shoulder can go longer than an hour at very low heat without drying; check at 45 minutes and again at 60.",
              "cause": "Overcooked, or pork shoulder cut too small.",
              "symptom": "Meat dry and stringy"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Blanquette de veau sits at the centre of French bourgeois cooking: elaborate without being showy, classic without being rigid. It is the kind of dish that takes a Sunday afternoon to make properly and is still worth it. Served with steamed rice or boiled new potatoes, with a cold glass of Chablis, it belongs to the category of meals that are as good for the cook's morale as for the guests'.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
